WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:15.510 align:middle line:90%


00:00:15.510 --> 00:00:17.510 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA MEREDITH: It
should come as no surprise

00:00:17.510 --> 00:00:20.030 align:middle line:84%
to learn that a college
degree is becoming essentially

00:00:20.030 --> 00:00:22.270 align:middle line:84%
worthless when it
comes to preparing one

00:00:22.270 --> 00:00:24.380 align:middle line:90%
for a life in today's world.

00:00:24.380 --> 00:00:26.920 align:middle line:84%
Dr. Carmen Boulter has
known this for decades.

00:00:26.920 --> 00:00:29.280 align:middle line:10%
In response, she began
creating a new model

00:00:29.280 --> 00:00:32.430 align:middle line:10%
for independent learning
as early as the 1980s

00:00:32.430 --> 00:00:35.370 align:middle line:10%
using computer technology
as the platform.

00:00:35.370 --> 00:00:38.860 align:middle line:10%
Today, she, trendcaster
Gerald Celente, and others

00:00:38.860 --> 00:00:41.600 align:middle line:10%
are openly suggesting
the majority of teens

00:00:41.600 --> 00:00:44.440 align:middle line:10%
should skip going into deep
debt for a college degree

00:00:44.440 --> 00:00:47.700 align:middle line:10%
only to be left with no useful
skills at the other end.

00:00:47.700 --> 00:00:50.700 align:middle line:84%
Instead, they can take control
of their own education,

00:00:50.700 --> 00:00:54.270 align:middle line:84%
tailoring it toward their
passions, skills, and desires.

00:00:54.270 --> 00:00:55.690 align:middle line:90%
Sounds good to me, Carmen.

00:00:55.690 --> 00:00:57.290 align:middle line:84%
Thank you so much
for joining us.

00:00:57.290 --> 00:00:58.970 align:middle line:84%
This is a really
important topic.

00:00:58.970 --> 00:01:00.950 align:middle line:84%
Before we start
talking, we're going

00:01:00.950 --> 00:01:02.609 align:middle line:84%
to run a little
video from YouTube

00:01:02.609 --> 00:01:03.900 align:middle line:90%
that you're very familiar with.

00:01:03.900 --> 00:01:05.850 align:middle line:90%
Gerald Celente is the producer.

00:01:05.850 --> 00:01:07.700 align:middle line:90%
It's called College Conspiracy.

00:01:07.700 --> 00:01:09.450 align:middle line:84%
And then I'd love to
have your reaction.

00:01:09.450 --> 00:01:10.750 align:middle line:90%
Let's take a look.

00:01:10.750 --> 00:01:14.020 align:middle line:84%
>>From the time an American
child reaches the sixth grade,

00:01:14.020 --> 00:01:16.830 align:middle line:84%
they are taught that the
key to success in life

00:01:16.830 --> 00:01:19.990 align:middle line:84%
is to do well in high school
so that they can get accepted

00:01:19.990 --> 00:01:21.680 align:middle line:90%
to the best possible college.

00:01:21.680 --> 00:01:24.510 align:middle line:84%
The better grades they get in
high school, the better college

00:01:24.510 --> 00:01:26.490 align:middle line:84%
they will have an
opportunity to get into.

00:01:26.490 --> 00:01:29.030 align:middle line:84%
They are taught that if they
get into a great college

00:01:29.030 --> 00:01:31.820 align:middle line:84%
and get their college
degree, any type of job

00:01:31.820 --> 00:01:34.320 align:middle line:84%
they desire in the
field of their choice

00:01:34.320 --> 00:01:36.110 align:middle line:90%
will be there waiting for them.

00:01:36.110 --> 00:01:37.910 align:middle line:84%
After getting their
dream job, they

00:01:37.910 --> 00:01:40.590 align:middle line:84%
will be able to buy any
car and house they desire,

00:01:40.590 --> 00:01:44.990 align:middle line:84%
start their own family, and
live the American dream.

00:01:44.990 --> 00:01:47.660 align:middle line:84%
Most Americans today
have an expectation

00:01:47.660 --> 00:01:50.250 align:middle line:84%
of future economic
success simply

00:01:50.250 --> 00:01:52.510 align:middle line:90%
by obtaining a college degree.

00:01:52.510 --> 00:01:54.590 align:middle line:10%
The entire purpose
of elementary school

00:01:54.590 --> 00:01:56.730 align:middle line:10%
is to prepare students
for high school,

00:01:56.730 --> 00:01:58.750 align:middle line:10%
and the entire
purpose of high school

00:01:58.750 --> 00:02:00.980 align:middle line:10%
is to prepare
students for college.

00:02:00.980 --> 00:02:05.090 align:middle line:10%
In fact, the US now has hundreds
of private college preparatory

00:02:05.090 --> 00:02:09.350 align:middle line:10%
high schools that, at a
cost of $25,000 per year,

00:02:09.350 --> 00:02:11.750 align:middle line:10%
are supposed to increase
students' chances of getting

00:02:11.750 --> 00:02:14.360 align:middle line:10%
into a top tier college.

00:02:14.360 --> 00:02:16.510 align:middle line:84%
Students are taught to
believe that if they don't

00:02:16.510 --> 00:02:18.930 align:middle line:84%
go to college, they will
be on a path to nowhere,

00:02:18.930 --> 00:02:23.510 align:middle line:84%
and will have no chance of ever
building a successful career.

00:02:23.510 --> 00:02:25.680 align:middle line:84%
Government regulations
like No Child

00:02:25.680 --> 00:02:29.680 align:middle line:84%
Left Behind have left grade
and high schools in shambles.

00:02:29.680 --> 00:02:31.560 align:middle line:84%
Instead of teachers
having the freedom

00:02:31.560 --> 00:02:35.500 align:middle line:84%
to think outside the box and use
creative techniques to prepare

00:02:35.500 --> 00:02:37.210 align:middle line:84%
their students for
the real world,

00:02:37.210 --> 00:02:39.490 align:middle line:84%
they are forced to
be narrow minded

00:02:39.490 --> 00:02:42.220 align:middle line:84%
and teach with worthless
information that will never

00:02:42.220 --> 00:02:44.940 align:middle line:84%
help their students
have successful careers.

00:02:44.940 --> 00:02:48.230 align:middle line:84%
Today, there are no high
schools left in America

00:02:48.230 --> 00:02:51.060 align:middle line:84%
that teach students the
knowledge necessary to start

00:02:51.060 --> 00:02:53.540 align:middle line:84%
their own business,
invent their own product,

00:02:53.540 --> 00:02:57.450 align:middle line:84%
or even how to use the internet
and other free resources

00:02:57.450 --> 00:03:02.280 align:middle line:84%
to become educated about things
without attending college.

00:03:02.280 --> 00:03:03.980 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: So what say ye?

00:03:03.980 --> 00:03:06.130 align:middle line:84%
That sounds like an
old model for sure,

00:03:06.130 --> 00:03:08.136 align:middle line:84%
but it doesn't sound like
what's working today.

00:03:08.136 --> 00:03:10.010 align:middle line:84%
>>CARMEN BOULTER: It
certainly isn't working.

00:03:10.010 --> 00:03:14.310 align:middle line:84%
In fact, only 32% of students
that graduate from high school

00:03:14.310 --> 00:03:17.370 align:middle line:84%
have the skills necessary
to do college work.

00:03:17.370 --> 00:03:18.065 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: 32%?

00:03:18.065 --> 00:03:18.731 align:middle line:90%
>>BOULTER: Yeah.

00:03:18.731 --> 00:03:19.846 align:middle line:90%
That comes from Harvard.

00:03:19.846 --> 00:03:22.470 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And that's because of
a lowering of the standards all

00:03:22.470 --> 00:03:24.767 align:middle line:84%
the way around, academically
and otherwise, I assume.

00:03:24.767 --> 00:03:26.600 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: I'm very
concerned about literacy

00:03:26.600 --> 00:03:28.350 align:middle line:90%
in the States and Canada.

00:03:28.350 --> 00:03:31.270 align:middle line:84%
There's many, many
things that are gone awry

00:03:31.270 --> 00:03:33.750 align:middle line:90%
with the education system.

00:03:33.750 --> 00:03:36.180 align:middle line:84%
They don't teach
cross-disciplinary things.

00:03:36.180 --> 00:03:39.110 align:middle line:90%
They have individual subjects.

00:03:39.110 --> 00:03:40.940 align:middle line:10%
And the students are
constantly interrupted

00:03:40.940 --> 00:03:43.450 align:middle line:10%
with announcements and whatnot.

00:03:43.450 --> 00:03:45.300 align:middle line:10%
They have to finish
things on the bell.

00:03:45.300 --> 00:03:47.750 align:middle line:10%
There's all kinds of
things that are regimented.

00:03:47.750 --> 00:03:50.359 align:middle line:10%
And the truth is is
that school buildings

00:03:50.359 --> 00:03:52.400 align:middle line:10%
are built by the same
companies that build jails.

00:03:52.400 --> 00:03:53.983 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: I was going
to bring that up

00:03:53.983 --> 00:03:56.440 align:middle line:10%
in a little bit--
that build prisons.

00:03:56.440 --> 00:03:57.440 align:middle line:90%
>>BOULTER: Prisons, yes.

00:03:57.440 --> 00:03:59.130 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And you know, it's
no surprise that schools

00:03:59.130 --> 00:04:00.922 align:middle line:84%
feel like a prison to
most of the children.

00:04:00.922 --> 00:04:03.171 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: Well, and they
have to go through scanners,

00:04:03.171 --> 00:04:04.680 align:middle line:84%
they have to pay
attention to bells,

00:04:04.680 --> 00:04:07.040 align:middle line:84%
there's policemen
in the schools,

00:04:07.040 --> 00:04:08.810 align:middle line:90%
and everything is regimented.

00:04:08.810 --> 00:04:11.511 align:middle line:84%
And this does not
foster creativity.

00:04:11.511 --> 00:04:12.385 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It doesn't.

00:04:12.385 --> 00:04:13.796 align:middle line:84%
And aside from
that, just looking

00:04:13.796 --> 00:04:16.220 align:middle line:84%
at the-- more of the rhythm
of the brain of younger

00:04:16.220 --> 00:04:18.980 align:middle line:84%
children in particular,
and up through teens,

00:04:18.980 --> 00:04:20.890 align:middle line:84%
the studies have
shown a lot of kids

00:04:20.890 --> 00:04:23.430 align:middle line:84%
simply are not even
awake enough to start

00:04:23.430 --> 00:04:25.870 align:middle line:84%
learning until it's
later in the morning.

00:04:25.870 --> 00:04:28.530 align:middle line:84%
I mean, just looking on
a rhythmic level in terms

00:04:28.530 --> 00:04:30.180 align:middle line:84%
of the time we start
school so that it

00:04:30.180 --> 00:04:33.470 align:middle line:84%
can coincide with daycare and
parents getting off to work

00:04:33.470 --> 00:04:34.460 align:middle line:90%
and so forth.

00:04:34.460 --> 00:04:35.777 align:middle line:90%
That's not working, either.

00:04:35.777 --> 00:04:37.360 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: Well, the
simple way to put

00:04:37.360 --> 00:04:41.100 align:middle line:84%
it is that we've fostered
teacher centered teaching

00:04:41.100 --> 00:04:43.885 align:middle line:84%
instead of learner
centered learning.

00:04:43.885 --> 00:04:47.427 align:middle line:84%
And that is the easiest way
to describe the problem.

00:04:47.427 --> 00:04:49.010 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well,
before we go into some

00:04:49.010 --> 00:04:51.340 align:middle line:84%
of the other
significant problems

00:04:51.340 --> 00:04:53.200 align:middle line:84%
that are going on
there, first of all,

00:04:53.200 --> 00:04:55.526 align:middle line:90%
you have how many degrees?

00:04:55.526 --> 00:04:58.050 align:middle line:90%
>>BOULTER: Five.

00:04:58.050 --> 00:05:00.510 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I mean, I'm
just bringing that up

00:05:00.510 --> 00:05:02.710 align:middle line:90%
as a point of irony here.

00:05:02.710 --> 00:05:05.114 align:middle line:84%
You have a couple
Ph.D.s, a couple masters.

00:05:05.114 --> 00:05:06.030 align:middle line:90%
Two or three master's?

00:05:06.030 --> 00:05:06.410 align:middle line:90%
>>BOULTER: One master's.

00:05:06.410 --> 00:05:07.170 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: One master?

00:05:07.170 --> 00:05:07.460 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:05:07.460 --> 00:05:08.480 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: I have
a college degree.

00:05:08.480 --> 00:05:08.870 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:05:08.870 --> 00:05:09.435 align:middle line:90%
>>BOULTER: Two bachelor's.

00:05:09.435 --> 00:05:09.850 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:05:09.850 --> 00:05:12.183 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: A master's, and I
actually did a Ph.D. twice.

00:05:12.183 --> 00:05:14.370 align:middle line:84%
I finished a Ph.D., and
I didn't have anybody

00:05:14.370 --> 00:05:16.516 align:middle line:84%
to supervise my
research, so then I

00:05:16.516 --> 00:05:18.140 align:middle line:84%
started over again
and did another one.

00:05:18.140 --> 00:05:19.250 align:middle line:90%
So that would add up to six.

00:05:19.250 --> 00:05:20.660 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That
would add up to six.

00:05:20.660 --> 00:05:21.159 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:05:21.159 --> 00:05:24.580 align:middle line:84%
So it's not as though you have
a bone with education at all.

00:05:24.580 --> 00:05:25.690 align:middle line:90%
It's not that.

00:05:25.690 --> 00:05:28.527 align:middle line:84%
Obviously, you find
great value in it

00:05:28.527 --> 00:05:29.610 align:middle line:90%
in your own personal life.

00:05:29.610 --> 00:05:32.600 align:middle line:84%
You've been able to spin off
amazing works and projects

00:05:32.600 --> 00:05:35.410 align:middle line:84%
through your life as a
result of this education.

00:05:35.410 --> 00:05:36.990 align:middle line:84%
You're just saying
the way it's being

00:05:36.990 --> 00:05:38.780 align:middle line:90%
done is no longer working.

00:05:38.780 --> 00:05:39.780 align:middle line:90%
>>BOULTER: That's right.

00:05:39.780 --> 00:05:42.850 align:middle line:84%
I started studying alternative
education way back when,

00:05:42.850 --> 00:05:46.780 align:middle line:84%
and looking at how students
could be more served.

00:05:46.780 --> 00:05:50.070 align:middle line:84%
And I also looked at the idea
of different learning styles--

00:05:50.070 --> 00:05:52.110 align:middle line:90%
auditory, visual, kinesthetic.

00:05:52.110 --> 00:05:53.800 align:middle line:90%
Multiple intelligences.

00:05:53.800 --> 00:05:55.640 align:middle line:84%
We have mathematical
intelligence,

00:05:55.640 --> 00:05:58.710 align:middle line:84%
we have musical intelligence,
interpersonal, intrapersonal,

00:05:58.710 --> 00:06:01.310 align:middle line:84%
and it goes on from
there-- scientific-- and we

00:06:01.310 --> 00:06:03.500 align:middle line:84%
need to be feeding all
these things in children.

00:06:03.500 --> 00:06:06.030 align:middle line:84%
But things need to be
combined, you know?

00:06:06.030 --> 00:06:09.230 align:middle line:84%
Like, why can't different
subjects be blended together?

00:06:09.230 --> 00:06:11.150 align:middle line:84%
And so things in schools
are very regimented,

00:06:11.150 --> 00:06:12.566 align:middle line:84%
and it doesn't
work for the brain.

00:06:12.566 --> 00:06:14.104 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't work for the student.

00:06:14.104 --> 00:06:15.770 align:middle line:84%
But what's been
happening is governments

00:06:15.770 --> 00:06:18.520 align:middle line:84%
are looking for numbers,
grades, and tests.

00:06:18.520 --> 00:06:22.260 align:middle line:84%
And test-driven education is
really detrimental to students.

00:06:22.260 --> 00:06:23.650 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Absolutely.

00:06:23.650 --> 00:06:24.580 align:middle line:90%
And teachers.

00:06:24.580 --> 00:06:25.680 align:middle line:90%
>>BOULTER: And teachers.

00:06:25.680 --> 00:06:29.470 align:middle line:84%
And so teachers are among the
most traditional of humans,

00:06:29.470 --> 00:06:31.201 align:middle line:84%
and they work to
rule a lot of them.

00:06:31.201 --> 00:06:33.700 align:middle line:84%
I mean, teachers are really
good people, but a lot of them--

00:06:33.700 --> 00:06:34.908 align:middle line:90%
don't give me anything extra.

00:06:34.908 --> 00:06:37.350 align:middle line:84%
Don't make me have a
different bag of tricks.

00:06:37.350 --> 00:06:38.994 align:middle line:90%
I want to do what's simple.

00:06:38.994 --> 00:06:40.160 align:middle line:90%
And they don't seem to care.

00:06:40.160 --> 00:06:42.510 align:middle line:84%
And it's interesting, it's
ironic, No Child Left Behind,

00:06:42.510 --> 00:06:44.010 align:middle line:84%
because I think
most of the children

00:06:44.010 --> 00:06:46.040 align:middle line:84%
are completely
being left behind.

00:06:46.040 --> 00:06:47.060 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Absolutely.

00:06:47.060 --> 00:06:49.220 align:middle line:84%
Now what was-- theoretically,
what was that agenda

00:06:49.220 --> 00:06:52.245 align:middle line:84%
supposed to be, and what
did it actually become?

00:06:52.245 --> 00:06:53.870 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: Well, I
think it's top down.

00:06:53.870 --> 00:06:54.800 align:middle line:90%
It's administrative.

00:06:54.800 --> 00:06:56.140 align:middle line:90%
It's government heavy.

00:06:56.140 --> 00:06:58.140 align:middle line:84%
And it's trying to prove
things through numbers

00:06:58.140 --> 00:06:59.470 align:middle line:90%
that aren't relevant.

00:06:59.470 --> 00:07:01.510 align:middle line:84%
So in research, there's
two different things

00:07:01.510 --> 00:07:05.560 align:middle line:84%
that we pay attention to--
validity and reliability.

00:07:05.560 --> 00:07:08.240 align:middle line:84%
And validity is are we measuring
what we think we're measuring?

00:07:08.240 --> 00:07:10.620 align:middle line:84%
So they say we're measuring
someone's skill set

00:07:10.620 --> 00:07:14.090 align:middle line:84%
by giving them a test, but
with multiple choice tests,

00:07:14.090 --> 00:07:17.210 align:middle line:84%
every single A, B,
C, D is debatable.

00:07:17.210 --> 00:07:20.170 align:middle line:84%
But the answer that the teacher
wants is the right answer,

00:07:20.170 --> 00:07:24.060 align:middle line:84%
and you could be able to
argue how B has its points,

00:07:24.060 --> 00:07:25.460 align:middle line:90%
has its merits.

00:07:25.460 --> 00:07:26.919 align:middle line:84%
But a multiple
choice test is going

00:07:26.919 --> 00:07:28.626 align:middle line:84%
to be able to go
through a little machine

00:07:28.626 --> 00:07:29.835 align:middle line:90%
and get the score right away.

00:07:29.835 --> 00:07:31.460 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But again,
this is so narrow.

00:07:31.460 --> 00:07:34.810 align:middle line:84%
This is such a narrow
way of evaluating

00:07:34.810 --> 00:07:37.380 align:middle line:90%
a person's intelligence.

00:07:37.380 --> 00:07:39.545 align:middle line:84%
I mean, knowledge is one
thing, but intelligence.

00:07:39.545 --> 00:07:40.920 align:middle line:84%
And when we're
talking knowledge,

00:07:40.920 --> 00:07:42.060 align:middle line:84%
I don't mean deep
inner knowledge,

00:07:42.060 --> 00:07:43.210 align:middle line:84%
and I want to get
to that in a moment.

00:07:43.210 --> 00:07:45.543 align:middle line:84%
We're talking about what has
been stuffed into the brain

00:07:45.543 --> 00:07:46.391 align:middle line:90%
randomly.

00:07:46.391 --> 00:07:48.390 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: Well, and these
tests-- like in Asia,

00:07:48.390 --> 00:07:52.060 align:middle line:84%
for example-- they'll give a
test in grade eight one time,

00:07:52.060 --> 00:07:54.830 align:middle line:84%
and you get A, B, C, D,
in terms of the levels.

00:07:54.830 --> 00:07:58.310 align:middle line:84%
If you're in A, B, you can
go on to the better level

00:07:58.310 --> 00:07:59.210 align:middle line:90%
universities.

00:07:59.210 --> 00:08:02.390 align:middle line:84%
If you're in C, D, you're
considered a dropout,

00:08:02.390 --> 00:08:04.320 align:middle line:84%
and there's almost no
place for you to go.

00:08:04.320 --> 00:08:06.680 align:middle line:84%
Well, what if your parents
had a fight the night before?

00:08:06.680 --> 00:08:07.920 align:middle line:90%
What if you don't feel well?

00:08:07.920 --> 00:08:10.480 align:middle line:84%
What if you're allergic to
the food you had for lunch?

00:08:10.480 --> 00:08:12.860 align:middle line:90%
And then you're labeled forever.

00:08:12.860 --> 00:08:14.010 align:middle line:90%
That's not fair.

00:08:14.010 --> 00:08:15.230 align:middle line:90%
And the pressure of that.

00:08:15.230 --> 00:08:16.730 align:middle line:84%
It's almost like
your blood pressure

00:08:16.730 --> 00:08:18.040 align:middle line:84%
going up when you
go to the doctor

00:08:18.040 --> 00:08:20.210 align:middle line:84%
because you're afraid they're
going to medicate you.

00:08:20.210 --> 00:08:21.085 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Absolutely.

00:08:21.085 --> 00:08:23.750 align:middle line:84%
And you hear about suicides
among young children in Japan

00:08:23.750 --> 00:08:26.020 align:middle line:84%
as a result of this-- of
disappointing the family

00:08:26.020 --> 00:08:28.280 align:middle line:84%
that they didn't make the
grade to get into the school

00:08:28.280 --> 00:08:30.020 align:middle line:84%
that their mother and
father had chosen for them.

00:08:30.020 --> 00:08:30.360 align:middle line:90%
>>BOULTER: Yeah.

00:08:30.360 --> 00:08:31.169 align:middle line:90%
None of that works.

00:08:31.169 --> 00:08:31.960 align:middle line:90%
None of that works.

00:08:31.960 --> 00:08:32.559 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: No.

00:08:32.559 --> 00:08:35.900 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: And the problem
is it's not constructivist.

00:08:35.900 --> 00:08:38.260 align:middle line:84%
And so when we look at
theories of learning,

00:08:38.260 --> 00:08:40.740 align:middle line:84%
the importance is to
build on what you know.

00:08:40.740 --> 00:08:42.990 align:middle line:84%
And so everybody comes in
with gaps in their learning,

00:08:42.990 --> 00:08:45.920 align:middle line:84%
particularly in language
learning, right?

00:08:45.920 --> 00:08:49.010 align:middle line:84%
And so people don't
start in the same place.

00:08:49.010 --> 00:08:51.660 align:middle line:84%
But the other thing
is meaning centered.

00:08:51.660 --> 00:08:53.590 align:middle line:84%
Most of what we're
doing in schools

00:08:53.590 --> 00:08:56.310 align:middle line:84%
right now is not
meaningful at all.

00:08:56.310 --> 00:08:59.890 align:middle line:84%
But especially now with
smartphones and internet,

00:08:59.890 --> 00:09:03.930 align:middle line:84%
memorizing lists of facts
is completely irrelevant.

00:09:03.930 --> 00:09:07.220 align:middle line:84%
A, you can access them
easily, but B, in 15 minutes,

00:09:07.220 --> 00:09:10.700 align:middle line:84%
if you knew every single thing
on internet, in 15 minutes,

00:09:10.700 --> 00:09:13.130 align:middle line:84%
it's irrelevant, because
things keep changing.

00:09:13.130 --> 00:09:14.880 align:middle line:84%
And what they're
using in schools

00:09:14.880 --> 00:09:17.520 align:middle line:84%
is textbooks with 20
year old information

00:09:17.520 --> 00:09:22.250 align:middle line:84%
that cost $200, when you can
get all the information online

00:09:22.250 --> 00:09:24.100 align:middle line:90%
in a more colorful way.

00:09:24.100 --> 00:09:24.910 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:09:24.910 --> 00:09:28.140 align:middle line:90%
And also, in an interactive way.

00:09:28.140 --> 00:09:29.470 align:middle line:90%
And, as you say, colorful.

00:09:29.470 --> 00:09:30.680 align:middle line:90%
Multimedia.

00:09:30.680 --> 00:09:32.190 align:middle line:90%
Let's back up.

00:09:32.190 --> 00:09:33.830 align:middle line:84%
In our last
conversation, which we

00:09:33.830 --> 00:09:38.570 align:middle line:84%
had this wonderful conversation
about the 18th dynasty

00:09:38.570 --> 00:09:42.270 align:middle line:84%
in Egypt, and about the
matriarchy in Egypt.

00:09:42.270 --> 00:09:45.540 align:middle line:84%
And going back into that,
you spoke of the fact

00:09:45.540 --> 00:09:47.670 align:middle line:84%
that once upon a
time, human beings

00:09:47.670 --> 00:09:51.780 align:middle line:84%
were utilizing 360
senses, which, obviously,

00:09:51.780 --> 00:09:55.030 align:middle line:84%
has to be extending all of us
out into all of that in order

00:09:55.030 --> 00:09:56.470 align:middle line:90%
to bring that in.

00:09:56.470 --> 00:10:01.340 align:middle line:84%
Now what we have is this is
narrowed down to five senses--

00:10:01.340 --> 00:10:02.240 align:middle line:90%
six, if you're lucky.

00:10:02.240 --> 00:10:05.040 align:middle line:84%
You have a little
intuition going for you.

00:10:05.040 --> 00:10:10.850 align:middle line:84%
What happens with a child,
for example, when-- well,

00:10:10.850 --> 00:10:13.300 align:middle line:84%
for example, until the last
100 years, we didn't all read.

00:10:13.300 --> 00:10:16.440 align:middle line:84%
The population at large
did not read, right?

00:10:16.440 --> 00:10:18.380 align:middle line:84%
Historically, that
was for initiates.

00:10:18.380 --> 00:10:19.430 align:middle line:90%
It was for professors.

00:10:19.430 --> 00:10:20.630 align:middle line:90%
It was for the learned.

00:10:20.630 --> 00:10:22.510 align:middle line:90%
The average person did not.

00:10:22.510 --> 00:10:27.620 align:middle line:84%
What has that done
to our brains,

00:10:27.620 --> 00:10:31.250 align:middle line:84%
to start taking information
in in digital form like that,

00:10:31.250 --> 00:10:34.310 align:middle line:84%
as opposed to a more
holistic kind of learning?

00:10:34.310 --> 00:10:35.749 align:middle line:90%
Good and bad.

00:10:35.749 --> 00:10:37.790 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: Well, education
is for the left brain.

00:10:37.790 --> 00:10:38.900 align:middle line:90%
That's all there is to it.

00:10:38.900 --> 00:10:41.210 align:middle line:84%
Reading, writing,
arithmetic-- what you can see.

00:10:41.210 --> 00:10:42.640 align:middle line:90%
Mechanical things.

00:10:42.640 --> 00:10:47.550 align:middle line:84%
And the whole brain is
involving symbolism and mystery

00:10:47.550 --> 00:10:50.540 align:middle line:84%
and impressions and art
and that sort of thing.

00:10:50.540 --> 00:10:52.540 align:middle line:90%
And that's just been locked off.

00:10:52.540 --> 00:10:57.180 align:middle line:84%
We really have isolated the
entirety of the left brain

00:10:57.180 --> 00:10:57.990 align:middle line:90%
thinking.

00:10:57.990 --> 00:10:59.710 align:middle line:90%
And that just doesn't work.

00:10:59.710 --> 00:11:01.740 align:middle line:84%
I mean, that creates
all kinds of imbalances.

00:11:01.740 --> 00:11:03.823 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, and we
even relegated the ancients

00:11:03.823 --> 00:11:09.200 align:middle line:84%
to, essentially, uneducated
savages who left nothing

00:11:09.200 --> 00:11:12.890 align:middle line:84%
but a few symbols behind
for us in these great works.

00:11:12.890 --> 00:11:15.680 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: Well, that's
just patriarchal ways

00:11:15.680 --> 00:11:18.720 align:middle line:84%
of being and thinking that
have just been pushed on us.

00:11:18.720 --> 00:11:20.830 align:middle line:90%
And it's all a dominator model.

00:11:20.830 --> 00:11:22.910 align:middle line:84%
And so in the current
education system,

00:11:22.910 --> 00:11:24.670 align:middle line:90%
the teacher is the dominator.

00:11:24.670 --> 00:11:26.990 align:middle line:84%
The person standing at the
front has the knowledge

00:11:26.990 --> 00:11:29.210 align:middle line:84%
and the power, and the
people sitting in the chairs

00:11:29.210 --> 00:11:30.260 align:middle line:90%
don't have anything.

00:11:30.260 --> 00:11:31.417 align:middle line:90%
But that doesn't work.

00:11:31.417 --> 00:11:33.000 align:middle line:84%
And so if you look
at online learning,

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:35.070 align:middle line:90%
it flattens the hierarchies.

00:11:35.070 --> 00:11:37.640 align:middle line:84%
Everybody becomes a teacher,
everybody becomes a learner,

00:11:37.640 --> 00:11:39.250 align:middle line:90%
and things go around.

00:11:39.250 --> 00:11:41.020 align:middle line:84%
But when you think
of interactivity,

00:11:41.020 --> 00:11:43.610 align:middle line:84%
if you look to learning
theory, interactivity

00:11:43.610 --> 00:11:45.710 align:middle line:90%
is the key to learning.

00:11:45.710 --> 00:11:48.060 align:middle line:90%
So there's six different things.

00:11:48.060 --> 00:11:50.170 align:middle line:84%
The student interacting
with the material,

00:11:50.170 --> 00:11:52.150 align:middle line:84%
the student interacting
with the teacher,

00:11:52.150 --> 00:11:53.920 align:middle line:84%
students interacting
with each other,

00:11:53.920 --> 00:11:56.870 align:middle line:84%
teachers interacting with each
other, and then the material

00:11:56.870 --> 00:11:59.470 align:middle line:84%
interacting in some
way, through people

00:11:59.470 --> 00:12:01.100 align:middle line:90%
looking at various projects.

00:12:01.100 --> 00:12:03.205 align:middle line:84%
Well, some people say
that if you're online,

00:12:03.205 --> 00:12:04.900 align:middle line:90%
you don't get any interactivity.

00:12:04.900 --> 00:12:06.670 align:middle line:84%
It couldn't be further
from the truth.

00:12:06.670 --> 00:12:09.020 align:middle line:84%
And so some people say if
you're doing online learning,

00:12:09.020 --> 00:12:10.340 align:middle line:84%
you spend the day
at the computer.

00:12:10.340 --> 00:12:11.715 align:middle line:84%
But you could be
doing a research

00:12:11.715 --> 00:12:15.940 align:middle line:84%
project in a kayak on seal
behavior, and film it,

00:12:15.940 --> 00:12:18.480 align:middle line:84%
and then go back to your
computer and plug it in.

00:12:18.480 --> 00:12:19.660 align:middle line:90%
It takes about two minutes.

00:12:19.660 --> 00:12:22.430 align:middle line:84%
And then let it upload and
then come back and unplug it.

00:12:22.430 --> 00:12:24.440 align:middle line:84%
You were not sitting at
the computer all day.

00:12:24.440 --> 00:12:26.430 align:middle line:84%
But you communicated
the information

00:12:26.430 --> 00:12:27.560 align:middle line:90%
through the computer.

00:12:27.560 --> 00:12:30.554 align:middle line:84%
So there's a lot of misnomers
about how students shouldn't

00:12:30.554 --> 00:12:32.220 align:middle line:84%
have their cell phones
in the classroom.

00:12:32.220 --> 00:12:32.860 align:middle line:90%
Why not?

00:12:32.860 --> 00:12:34.730 align:middle line:84%
I used to say, when
I taught in Taiwan--

00:12:34.730 --> 00:12:36.271 align:middle line:84%
I've taught at many
different levels,

00:12:36.271 --> 00:12:38.190 align:middle line:84%
and I also taught
in Asia at a college

00:12:38.190 --> 00:12:39.664 align:middle line:90%
that became a university.

00:12:39.664 --> 00:12:41.080 align:middle line:84%
If you can't beat
them, join them.

00:12:41.080 --> 00:12:43.230 align:middle line:84%
If they've got these
cell phones and they

00:12:43.230 --> 00:12:45.630 align:middle line:84%
can make videos and
edit them, why not

00:12:45.630 --> 00:12:48.220 align:middle line:84%
let that be part of
their presentation?

00:12:48.220 --> 00:12:50.970 align:middle line:84%
So there's so much technology
that can help people,

00:12:50.970 --> 00:12:53.050 align:middle line:84%
and yet you see, if
you go down the hall

00:12:53.050 --> 00:12:57.310 align:middle line:84%
in a school, people sitting in
front of worksheets, totally

00:12:57.310 --> 00:12:59.620 align:middle line:90%
quiet, and their little pencil.

00:12:59.620 --> 00:13:03.390 align:middle line:84%
And I have recently done an
evaluation of a full program

00:13:03.390 --> 00:13:04.200 align:middle line:90%
at a university.

00:13:04.200 --> 00:13:07.380 align:middle line:84%
I was asked to be
a peer consultant.

00:13:07.380 --> 00:13:09.550 align:middle line:84%
And they were all
complaining that they

00:13:09.550 --> 00:13:11.890 align:middle line:84%
didn't have enough
funding for professors.

00:13:11.890 --> 00:13:14.310 align:middle line:84%
And they were spending
the exact amount

00:13:14.310 --> 00:13:17.982 align:middle line:84%
of a professor's salary
for a year on photocopying.

00:13:17.982 --> 00:13:18.690 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Really?

00:13:18.690 --> 00:13:19.315 align:middle line:90%
>>BOULTER: Yep.

00:13:19.315 --> 00:13:22.910 align:middle line:84%
And when you say, stop that,
they don't know what to do.

00:13:22.910 --> 00:13:24.790 align:middle line:84%
So they're handing
binders to each other.

00:13:24.790 --> 00:13:28.430 align:middle line:84%
They could be doing their
teacher meetings asynchronously

00:13:28.430 --> 00:13:31.490 align:middle line:84%
online, meaning
not in real time.

00:13:31.490 --> 00:13:33.650 align:middle line:84%
And when they get home,
they can run the meeting,

00:13:33.650 --> 00:13:36.130 align:middle line:84%
and they can make their
comments on a discussion board.

00:13:36.130 --> 00:13:38.350 align:middle line:84%
All these things
reduce the workload.

00:13:38.350 --> 00:13:41.710 align:middle line:84%
But when people look at what
it would take to change,

00:13:41.710 --> 00:13:44.210 align:middle line:84%
they get really scared,
because I can't take anymore.

00:13:44.210 --> 00:13:45.780 align:middle line:90%
I don't want to do anymore.

00:13:45.780 --> 00:13:47.170 align:middle line:90%
And it's really quite simple.

00:13:47.170 --> 00:13:50.440 align:middle line:84%
And so in my online courses,
I taught my students

00:13:50.440 --> 00:13:51.730 align:middle line:90%
to go paperless.

00:13:51.730 --> 00:13:53.520 align:middle line:90%
Paperless in the classroom.

00:13:53.520 --> 00:13:55.700 align:middle line:90%
And to be completely digital.

00:13:55.700 --> 00:13:57.695 align:middle line:84%
And it's delightful,
because it's

00:13:57.695 --> 00:14:00.467 align:middle line:84%
a completely different
way of teaching.

00:14:00.467 --> 00:14:02.800 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Going back into
what's already being done now,

00:14:02.800 --> 00:14:05.020 align:middle line:84%
some of the classical
ways, but offshoots

00:14:05.020 --> 00:14:09.720 align:middle line:84%
of that-- some of the systems
that are already in existence

00:14:09.720 --> 00:14:13.140 align:middle line:84%
are actually seemingly
working pretty well,

00:14:13.140 --> 00:14:15.760 align:middle line:84%
such as the Waldorf System,
and some of the other charter

00:14:15.760 --> 00:14:17.900 align:middle line:90%
school systems.

00:14:17.900 --> 00:14:20.140 align:middle line:84%
I have a fondness for
the Waldorf System,

00:14:20.140 --> 00:14:22.660 align:middle line:84%
simply because it
really did focus

00:14:22.660 --> 00:14:25.960 align:middle line:84%
on creativity first and a
more integrated approach

00:14:25.960 --> 00:14:27.040 align:middle line:90%
to learning.

00:14:27.040 --> 00:14:29.480 align:middle line:84%
And one of the things--
I mean, for example,

00:14:29.480 --> 00:14:33.171 align:middle line:84%
as a high schooler, you had to
be outdoors from first grade

00:14:33.171 --> 00:14:33.670 align:middle line:90%
on.

00:14:33.670 --> 00:14:35.990 align:middle line:10%
You had to be planting
seeds, and then

00:14:35.990 --> 00:14:37.840 align:middle line:10%
harvesting the
seeds in the fall,

00:14:37.840 --> 00:14:41.510 align:middle line:10%
and making your bread out of
them for whatever occasion.

00:14:41.510 --> 00:14:46.020 align:middle line:84%
And it's really a hands
on kind of education.

00:14:46.020 --> 00:14:48.170 align:middle line:84%
You're interacting
with the world.

00:14:48.170 --> 00:14:50.570 align:middle line:84%
Now, what about those
kinds of programs?

00:14:50.570 --> 00:14:53.110 align:middle line:84%
How does that interface with
what you're talking about?

00:14:53.110 --> 00:14:54.860 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: Well, to
me, that's the answer.

00:14:54.860 --> 00:14:55.700 align:middle line:90%
It's synthesized.

00:14:55.700 --> 00:14:58.000 align:middle line:90%
It's integrated in Waldorf.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.550 align:middle line:84%
They're doing signs
for the letters.

00:15:00.550 --> 00:15:01.751 align:middle line:90%
They're acting them out.

00:15:01.751 --> 00:15:03.500 align:middle line:84%
If they're putting
your feet on the ground

00:15:03.500 --> 00:15:05.150 align:middle line:84%
and putting their
hands in the ground,

00:15:05.150 --> 00:15:07.380 align:middle line:84%
they're actually
communing with nature.

00:15:07.380 --> 00:15:10.440 align:middle line:84%
But in the diagnostic
criteria for psychologists

00:15:10.440 --> 00:15:12.280 align:middle line:84%
and psychiatrists, the
new ones coming out,

00:15:12.280 --> 00:15:14.800 align:middle line:84%
there's such a thing
as nature deprivation.

00:15:14.800 --> 00:15:17.130 align:middle line:84%
So the obvious thing would
be to take these children,

00:15:17.130 --> 00:15:19.490 align:middle line:84%
take their shoes off, and
put them on the grass.

00:15:19.490 --> 00:15:21.531 align:middle line:84%
But what they're doing is
they're medicating them

00:15:21.531 --> 00:15:24.300 align:middle line:84%
with antidepressants with
a side effect of suicide.

00:15:24.300 --> 00:15:27.210 align:middle line:84%
Like, how is that ever
going to be a good idea?

00:15:27.210 --> 00:15:31.190 align:middle line:84%
But it's the way we've
deviated so far from nature,

00:15:31.190 --> 00:15:33.920 align:middle line:90%
and not valued that.

00:15:33.920 --> 00:15:36.500 align:middle line:84%
And so the Waldorf system,
the Montessori system,

00:15:36.500 --> 00:15:39.390 align:middle line:84%
that is the true essence
of alternative education

00:15:39.390 --> 00:15:41.940 align:middle line:84%
that's looking at
the whole person,

00:15:41.940 --> 00:15:44.180 align:middle line:84%
that puts the
students first, that

00:15:44.180 --> 00:15:46.600 align:middle line:84%
puts the way the
brain functions first.

00:15:46.600 --> 00:15:48.814 align:middle line:90%
To me, that's an answer.

00:15:48.814 --> 00:15:50.230 align:middle line:84%
But it's not
happening everywhere,

00:15:50.230 --> 00:15:51.125 align:middle line:84%
by any stretch of
the imagination.

00:15:51.125 --> 00:15:52.166 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: No, not at all.

00:15:52.166 --> 00:15:54.367 align:middle line:84%
I mean, there are few
Waldorf charter schools that

00:15:54.367 --> 00:15:56.700 align:middle line:84%
are starting to come up that
are publicly supported now,

00:15:56.700 --> 00:15:59.140 align:middle line:84%
which I find at
least a step forward.

00:15:59.140 --> 00:16:01.280 align:middle line:84%
What do you think--
now, stepping back

00:16:01.280 --> 00:16:04.310 align:middle line:84%
even further
philosophically, do you

00:16:04.310 --> 00:16:07.020 align:middle line:84%
think that there has been
a very specific agenda

00:16:07.020 --> 00:16:11.050 align:middle line:84%
as to the type of person
that the current type

00:16:11.050 --> 00:16:13.364 align:middle line:84%
of educational system
is churning out?

00:16:13.364 --> 00:16:14.780 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: Well,
we haven't really

00:16:14.780 --> 00:16:17.810 align:middle line:84%
changed our education
system in 100 years.

00:16:17.810 --> 00:16:19.520 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But in
that last 100 years,

00:16:19.520 --> 00:16:22.940 align:middle line:84%
do you think there was
actually some kind of agenda?

00:16:22.940 --> 00:16:23.650 align:middle line:90%
>>BOULTER: Yes.

00:16:23.650 --> 00:16:25.829 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And can you
explain what that is?

00:16:25.829 --> 00:16:27.370 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: What the
corporations were

00:16:27.370 --> 00:16:30.312 align:middle line:84%
looking for is obedient
factory workers.

00:16:30.312 --> 00:16:31.270 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: There you go.

00:16:31.270 --> 00:16:34.170 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: Not somebody who
could be creative and become

00:16:34.170 --> 00:16:37.390 align:middle line:84%
the corporation themselves--
run their own corporation.

00:16:37.390 --> 00:16:40.490 align:middle line:84%
And so we were never taught
how to balance our checkbook.

00:16:40.490 --> 00:16:42.650 align:middle line:84%
We were never taught
how to do life skills.

00:16:42.650 --> 00:16:44.620 align:middle line:84%
We were taught
systematic things that

00:16:44.620 --> 00:16:47.640 align:middle line:84%
could be measured in tests that
give you a score that tell you

00:16:47.640 --> 00:16:49.600 align:middle line:84%
if you're good or
bad, which isn't

00:16:49.600 --> 00:16:50.850 align:middle line:90%
dealing with the whole person.

00:16:50.850 --> 00:16:53.190 align:middle line:84%
Think of the waste
of human resources

00:16:53.190 --> 00:16:55.560 align:middle line:84%
with that, because people
aren't being creative.

00:16:55.560 --> 00:16:56.970 align:middle line:90%
Now, what is creative thinking?

00:16:56.970 --> 00:16:59.100 align:middle line:84%
Creative thinking,
technically-- I've studied this.

00:16:59.100 --> 00:17:02.150 align:middle line:84%
My master's research was on
it-- is the interactivity

00:17:02.150 --> 00:17:04.130 align:middle line:84%
between the two sides
of the brain, which

00:17:04.130 --> 00:17:05.890 align:middle line:84%
comes through the
corpus callosum.

00:17:05.890 --> 00:17:07.710 align:middle line:84%
And as we mentioned in
the other interview,

00:17:07.710 --> 00:17:10.079 align:middle line:84%
the Egyptians even had
crowns with snake figures

00:17:10.079 --> 00:17:11.736 align:middle line:84%
that went across
the corpus callosum.

00:17:11.736 --> 00:17:13.819 align:middle line:84%
And if you get stuck in
either side of your brain,

00:17:13.819 --> 00:17:16.420 align:middle line:84%
you're not able to
think creatively.

00:17:16.420 --> 00:17:17.920 align:middle line:84%
But that's not
what's being studied.

00:17:17.920 --> 00:17:19.930 align:middle line:84%
They're not asking
for creativity.

00:17:19.930 --> 00:17:22.119 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: In fact, as soon
as the budgets started

00:17:22.119 --> 00:17:24.728 align:middle line:84%
being slashed over the last
decade and a half or so,

00:17:24.728 --> 00:17:26.519 align:middle line:84%
the first thing that
went was art programs.

00:17:26.519 --> 00:17:27.520 align:middle line:90%
>>BOULTER: That's right.

00:17:27.520 --> 00:17:29.602 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And a lot of
physical education programs

00:17:29.602 --> 00:17:30.680 align:middle line:90%
started going after that.

00:17:30.680 --> 00:17:31.325 align:middle line:90%
>>BOULTER: And music.

00:17:31.325 --> 00:17:32.630 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Music started going.

00:17:32.630 --> 00:17:35.550 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: But they force
mathematical skills and science

00:17:35.550 --> 00:17:37.900 align:middle line:84%
skills on people who
are more artistic,

00:17:37.900 --> 00:17:39.447 align:middle line:90%
and the other way around.

00:17:39.447 --> 00:17:40.280 align:middle line:90%
And it doesn't work.

00:17:40.280 --> 00:17:41.696 align:middle line:84%
So they're really
literally trying

00:17:41.696 --> 00:17:43.140 align:middle line:90%
to force everybody into a mold.

00:17:43.140 --> 00:17:45.110 align:middle line:90%
And no one fits in those molds.

00:17:45.110 --> 00:17:47.794 align:middle line:84%
And so most students
are completely bored.

00:17:47.794 --> 00:17:49.710 align:middle line:84%
And if you think about
online learning-- let's

00:17:49.710 --> 00:17:51.840 align:middle line:84%
just talk about video
tutorials for a minute.

00:17:51.840 --> 00:17:54.560 align:middle line:84%
If you're learning the computer,
and you're in a classroom,

00:17:54.560 --> 00:17:56.430 align:middle line:84%
everyone's starting
in a different place,

00:17:56.430 --> 00:17:59.620 align:middle line:84%
and everybody has different
scaffolding and understanding

00:17:59.620 --> 00:18:00.570 align:middle line:90%
for their learning.

00:18:00.570 --> 00:18:04.080 align:middle line:84%
And so if you were doing a
series of video tutorials,

00:18:04.080 --> 00:18:07.560 align:middle line:84%
you alone may go through
one to three really quickly,

00:18:07.560 --> 00:18:10.010 align:middle line:84%
and on number four, you go,
I don't understand that.

00:18:10.010 --> 00:18:11.700 align:middle line:84%
And then you could
explore a little bit

00:18:11.700 --> 00:18:13.520 align:middle line:84%
and go and look at the
definition of terms.

00:18:13.520 --> 00:18:16.500 align:middle line:84%
Which definitions are
you not understanding?

00:18:16.500 --> 00:18:18.650 align:middle line:90%
Ask some questions about that.

00:18:18.650 --> 00:18:20.904 align:middle line:84%
Maybe review number
four 10 times.

00:18:20.904 --> 00:18:22.320 align:middle line:84%
But if you're
sitting by yourself,

00:18:22.320 --> 00:18:23.490 align:middle line:90%
no one knows you've done that.

00:18:23.490 --> 00:18:24.490 align:middle line:90%
Oh, five, six, seven, eight.

00:18:24.490 --> 00:18:25.532 align:middle line:90%
Oh, you get those, right?

00:18:25.532 --> 00:18:26.948 align:middle line:84%
But the person
sitting next to you

00:18:26.948 --> 00:18:28.580 align:middle line:84%
is going to get
stumped somewhere else.

00:18:28.580 --> 00:18:30.850 align:middle line:84%
So if you learn computers
or a certain subject

00:18:30.850 --> 00:18:33.547 align:middle line:84%
in the classroom, then you
have to wait for everybody

00:18:33.547 --> 00:18:34.880 align:middle line:90%
to get it as you're bored stiff.

00:18:34.880 --> 00:18:35.546 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:18:35.546 --> 00:18:37.650 align:middle line:84%
It can move no faster
than the slowest person.

00:18:37.650 --> 00:18:38.750 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: No, but
then when it comes time

00:18:38.750 --> 00:18:40.335 align:middle line:84%
and you don't understand,
it goes flying right

00:18:40.335 --> 00:18:41.890 align:middle line:84%
over your head, and they're
on to the next thing.

00:18:41.890 --> 00:18:42.215 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That, too.

00:18:42.215 --> 00:18:43.881 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: That's
completely not useful.

00:18:43.881 --> 00:18:46.050 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: You know,
there's a system--

00:18:46.050 --> 00:18:48.900 align:middle line:90%
there was a series of books.

00:18:48.900 --> 00:18:52.200 align:middle line:84%
You can call them whatever
you want to call them.

00:18:52.200 --> 00:18:53.740 align:middle line:84%
The Anastasia Ringing
Cedars series,

00:18:53.740 --> 00:18:55.450 align:middle line:84%
which I know you've
read and I've read,

00:18:55.450 --> 00:18:57.320 align:middle line:84%
and I just found them
magical, personally.

00:18:57.320 --> 00:18:59.610 align:middle line:84%
But one of the things I
was most intrigued with

00:18:59.610 --> 00:19:01.970 align:middle line:84%
was the way the children
were treated in the education

00:19:01.970 --> 00:19:02.770 align:middle line:90%
system.

00:19:02.770 --> 00:19:05.730 align:middle line:84%
And a couple of years
ago, something happened.

00:19:05.730 --> 00:19:06.850 align:middle line:90%
I was poised.

00:19:06.850 --> 00:19:09.000 align:middle line:84%
I was over in Eastern
Europe, ready to go

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:10.660 align:middle line:90%
do a story on that school.

00:19:10.660 --> 00:19:13.920 align:middle line:84%
I had seen a documentary,
because this Anastasia style

00:19:13.920 --> 00:19:16.020 align:middle line:90%
school had been created.

00:19:16.020 --> 00:19:17.620 align:middle line:84%
It's in Russia,
which, of course,

00:19:17.620 --> 00:19:19.180 align:middle line:90%
they're ahead in so many things.

00:19:19.180 --> 00:19:21.430 align:middle line:84%
But one of the things I
found fascinating about it

00:19:21.430 --> 00:19:23.900 align:middle line:84%
was that there
were no professors.

00:19:23.900 --> 00:19:27.070 align:middle line:84%
And again, there wasn't
the same kind of hierarchy.

00:19:27.070 --> 00:19:29.830 align:middle line:84%
I mean there was definitely an
agenda to keep the kids busy.

00:19:29.830 --> 00:19:31.840 align:middle line:90%
There was no idle time.

00:19:31.840 --> 00:19:33.002 align:middle line:90%
Kids do need idle time.

00:19:33.002 --> 00:19:34.460 align:middle line:84%
If there was a flaw
in the program,

00:19:34.460 --> 00:19:36.880 align:middle line:84%
I would say that it was
the lack of idle time.

00:19:36.880 --> 00:19:39.020 align:middle line:84%
But what was interesting
is if there was a subject

00:19:39.020 --> 00:19:44.250 align:middle line:84%
to be studied, you took people
from varying age groups.

00:19:44.250 --> 00:19:46.790 align:middle line:84%
You could have an 8 year
old in with an 18 year

00:19:46.790 --> 00:19:50.300 align:middle line:84%
old studying something
of a mechanical nature,

00:19:50.300 --> 00:19:52.360 align:middle line:84%
or something of a
scientific nature.

00:19:52.360 --> 00:19:56.420 align:middle line:84%
And together as a group,
they evaluated and studied

00:19:56.420 --> 00:19:59.460 align:middle line:84%
the subject completely
out until they

00:19:59.460 --> 00:20:03.640 align:middle line:84%
felt that they had complete
understanding of it.

00:20:03.640 --> 00:20:06.310 align:middle line:84%
And the only time a
teacher came into play

00:20:06.310 --> 00:20:07.950 align:middle line:84%
is if they felt
they were stumped,

00:20:07.950 --> 00:20:09.665 align:middle line:84%
and there was still
a missing piece.

00:20:09.665 --> 00:20:11.830 align:middle line:84%
They weren't connecting
the dots somewhere.

00:20:11.830 --> 00:20:13.920 align:middle line:84%
And sometimes, it might
be the youngest among them

00:20:13.920 --> 00:20:15.450 align:middle line:90%
who was the most brilliant.

00:20:15.450 --> 00:20:18.140 align:middle line:84%
So there was
literally no hierarchy

00:20:18.140 --> 00:20:19.560 align:middle line:90%
in the sense of learning.

00:20:19.560 --> 00:20:22.350 align:middle line:84%
What do you think about that--
that kind of immersion group

00:20:22.350 --> 00:20:23.190 align:middle line:90%
think?

00:20:23.190 --> 00:20:24.910 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: Well,
there's no hierarchy

00:20:24.910 --> 00:20:26.499 align:middle line:84%
in a matriarchal
culture, either.

00:20:26.499 --> 00:20:28.540 align:middle line:84%
Again, it's all about
flattening the hierarchies.

00:20:28.540 --> 00:20:30.260 align:middle line:84%
But think about a
family grouping.

00:20:30.260 --> 00:20:33.780 align:middle line:84%
And this extends-- there's a
child, there's an older child,

00:20:33.780 --> 00:20:35.050 align:middle line:90%
but even mommy and daddy.

00:20:35.050 --> 00:20:37.860 align:middle line:84%
So if there were two
teachers interacting

00:20:37.860 --> 00:20:40.150 align:middle line:84%
at the front of the room,
like mommy and daddy,

00:20:40.150 --> 00:20:41.670 align:middle line:84%
that's also useful
to the students.

00:20:41.670 --> 00:20:43.780 align:middle line:84%
One can be at the front,
one can be moving around.

00:20:43.780 --> 00:20:47.160 align:middle line:84%
But I always put my
students in family groupings

00:20:47.160 --> 00:20:49.110 align:middle line:84%
with a lower level student
with a higher level

00:20:49.110 --> 00:20:51.150 align:middle line:90%
student working together.

00:20:51.150 --> 00:20:52.970 align:middle line:84%
So the lower level
student says, well, I

00:20:52.970 --> 00:20:53.690 align:middle line:90%
don't know how to do that.

00:20:53.690 --> 00:20:54.814 align:middle line:90%
I never built a PowerPoint.

00:20:54.814 --> 00:20:56.270 align:middle line:90%
I'll go get the coffee.

00:20:56.270 --> 00:20:58.560 align:middle line:84%
But they're watching
someone else do it.

00:20:58.560 --> 00:21:00.870 align:middle line:84%
And modeling, in
my Ph.D. research,

00:21:00.870 --> 00:21:03.736 align:middle line:84%
it was all about what makes
people adopt technology.

00:21:03.736 --> 00:21:05.110 align:middle line:84%
And it's not just
having hardware

00:21:05.110 --> 00:21:06.580 align:middle line:90%
and software and stuff.

00:21:06.580 --> 00:21:07.600 align:middle line:90%
It's modeling.

00:21:07.600 --> 00:21:10.820 align:middle line:84%
And so if a lower level
person in the skills

00:21:10.820 --> 00:21:13.080 align:middle line:84%
can be with somebody
who knows more,

00:21:13.080 --> 00:21:15.900 align:middle line:84%
then they can get
it from modeling.

00:21:15.900 --> 00:21:18.350 align:middle line:84%
But also, a younger person is
going to approach something

00:21:18.350 --> 00:21:22.350 align:middle line:84%
from a more creative, or perhaps
a more inquisitive standpoint,

00:21:22.350 --> 00:21:24.260 align:middle line:90%
or even a colorful, artistic.

00:21:24.260 --> 00:21:25.990 align:middle line:84%
And the older person
can learn that.

00:21:25.990 --> 00:21:28.574 align:middle line:84%
But what we do is take all the
As, all the Bs, all the Cs, all

00:21:28.574 --> 00:21:30.823 align:middle line:84%
the Ds, and put them all in
groups, and then everybody

00:21:30.823 --> 00:21:32.590 align:middle line:84%
sits there and they
can't progress.

00:21:32.590 --> 00:21:36.140 align:middle line:84%
It's natural for
children in a family

00:21:36.140 --> 00:21:41.810 align:middle line:84%
to look up to certain people
and take care of children,

00:21:41.810 --> 00:21:43.250 align:middle line:90%
and everybody has their role.

00:21:43.250 --> 00:21:44.960 align:middle line:84%
And you can switch
out the roles.

00:21:44.960 --> 00:21:47.470 align:middle line:84%
So I think one of the most
damaging things in a classroom

00:21:47.470 --> 00:21:49.640 align:middle line:84%
setting is the fact that
there's only one teacher.

00:21:49.640 --> 00:21:50.223 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:21:50.223 --> 00:21:51.470 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, I agree with that.

00:21:51.470 --> 00:21:54.420 align:middle line:84%
And another thing, too, is
this notion of competition

00:21:54.420 --> 00:21:54.999 align:middle line:90%
that occurs.

00:21:54.999 --> 00:21:56.790 align:middle line:84%
I mean, there becomes
a classroom hierarchy

00:21:56.790 --> 00:21:58.870 align:middle line:84%
in terms of grading
and bell curves.

00:21:58.870 --> 00:22:01.700 align:middle line:84%
In that case, all artists get
left behind, for the most part.

00:22:01.700 --> 00:22:04.527 align:middle line:84%
It's usually the real
sensitives that are working more

00:22:04.527 --> 00:22:06.610 align:middle line:84%
on the right side of the
brain that aren't testing

00:22:06.610 --> 00:22:09.980 align:middle line:84%
out all that well when they may
be the most genius among them.

00:22:09.980 --> 00:22:11.720 align:middle line:84%
And one of the things
in this Waldorf

00:22:11.720 --> 00:22:14.700 align:middle line:84%
system I found
particularly lovely is--

00:22:14.700 --> 00:22:17.810 align:middle line:84%
my son went through the
system-- was his teacher

00:22:17.810 --> 00:22:19.521 align:middle line:84%
would tell the kids
when it was time.

00:22:19.521 --> 00:22:22.020 align:middle line:84%
When they were old enough to
start doing tests-- they really

00:22:22.020 --> 00:22:24.311 align:middle line:84%
don't grade them much until
they're around eighth grade

00:22:24.311 --> 00:22:28.660 align:middle line:84%
or so-- they would tell
the kids, help each other.

00:22:28.660 --> 00:22:29.890 align:middle line:90%
Here's your test.

00:22:29.890 --> 00:22:32.070 align:middle line:90%
Help each other out.

00:22:32.070 --> 00:22:33.790 align:middle line:90%
Elsewhere, it's called cheating.

00:22:33.790 --> 00:22:35.690 align:middle line:84%
But his feeling
was, what is there

00:22:35.690 --> 00:22:38.190 align:middle line:84%
to gain with someone
who's sitting there,

00:22:38.190 --> 00:22:40.190 align:middle line:84%
ignorant, unable to
answer questions.

00:22:40.190 --> 00:22:42.290 align:middle line:84%
Whether they're prepared
or not was irrelevant.

00:22:42.290 --> 00:22:45.839 align:middle line:84%
The point was, he believed that
the morale of the entire class

00:22:45.839 --> 00:22:48.130 align:middle line:84%
and the learning was going
to go to a much higher level

00:22:48.130 --> 00:22:49.437 align:middle line:90%
if you helped each other.

00:22:49.437 --> 00:22:51.020 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: But that's
a model for what

00:22:51.020 --> 00:22:53.500 align:middle line:84%
we should be doing
anyway in life.

00:22:53.500 --> 00:22:57.040 align:middle line:84%
Why should every individual
know everything at 100% level

00:22:57.040 --> 00:22:58.650 align:middle line:90%
when we have a team?

00:22:58.650 --> 00:23:00.940 align:middle line:84%
And so that's
completely appropriate.

00:23:00.940 --> 00:23:03.380 align:middle line:84%
And I do think that helping
each other is a good idea.

00:23:03.380 --> 00:23:06.760 align:middle line:84%
But the minute that you get a
test, the number and the score

00:23:06.760 --> 00:23:08.850 align:middle line:84%
on the test is a
self esteem value.

00:23:08.850 --> 00:23:09.660 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It is.

00:23:09.660 --> 00:23:11.129 align:middle line:90%
>>BOULTER: You got 70.

00:23:11.129 --> 00:23:12.670 align:middle line:84%
Well, that means
that you're no good.

00:23:12.670 --> 00:23:15.975 align:middle line:84%
So then if thought is creative,
the brain says, yes, boss,

00:23:15.975 --> 00:23:17.294 align:middle line:90%
you're no good.

00:23:17.294 --> 00:23:17.960 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:23:17.960 --> 00:23:19.300 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: So somebody
told you you were no good.

00:23:19.300 --> 00:23:20.770 align:middle line:84%
So then you go and write another
test, and you're no good.

00:23:20.770 --> 00:23:22.319 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Now you
have mass anxiety

00:23:22.319 --> 00:23:23.360 align:middle line:90%
going into the next test.

00:23:23.360 --> 00:23:24.900 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: And then you're
no good, so you give up.

00:23:24.900 --> 00:23:25.230 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:23:25.230 --> 00:23:26.190 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: How many
people give up?

00:23:26.190 --> 00:23:26.800 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:23:26.800 --> 00:23:28.800 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: But the thing
is, is what can you do?

00:23:28.800 --> 00:23:30.950 align:middle line:84%
And so I do not
teach with tests.

00:23:30.950 --> 00:23:32.470 align:middle line:84%
I don't see how
a test is useful.

00:23:32.470 --> 00:23:33.270 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Good for you.

00:23:33.270 --> 00:23:34.720 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: Because
all the students--

00:23:34.720 --> 00:23:35.790 align:middle line:90%
I want them to make something.

00:23:35.790 --> 00:23:36.956 align:middle line:90%
I want them to do a project.

00:23:36.956 --> 00:23:38.250 align:middle line:90%
I want them to speak about it.

00:23:38.250 --> 00:23:39.625 align:middle line:84%
I want them to
become articulate.

00:23:39.625 --> 00:23:40.650 align:middle line:90%
I want them to film.

00:23:40.650 --> 00:23:43.850 align:middle line:84%
I want them to make
something, create it,

00:23:43.850 --> 00:23:45.720 align:middle line:90%
and then it's theirs, right?

00:23:45.720 --> 00:23:47.860 align:middle line:84%
And so that's the
level that I'm going

00:23:47.860 --> 00:23:50.430 align:middle line:84%
to mark them on-- the
energy they put in.

00:23:50.430 --> 00:23:54.840 align:middle line:84%
Not on how good it was,
but how much they grew.

00:23:54.840 --> 00:23:58.220 align:middle line:84%
I was teaching in
Chinese culture in Taiwan

00:23:58.220 --> 00:24:00.560 align:middle line:84%
for four years, and
the students had

00:24:00.560 --> 00:24:02.260 align:middle line:84%
been taking English
for 10 years.

00:24:02.260 --> 00:24:03.510 align:middle line:90%
And they were mute.

00:24:03.510 --> 00:24:05.480 align:middle line:84%
They were so terrified
to ask a question--

00:24:05.480 --> 00:24:05.880 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: To be wrong.

00:24:05.880 --> 00:24:06.670 align:middle line:90%
>>BOULTER: And to be wrong.

00:24:06.670 --> 00:24:08.520 align:middle line:84%
And they were chastised
if they were wrong.

00:24:08.520 --> 00:24:11.250 align:middle line:84%
But the other thing is they
never asked questions or made

00:24:11.250 --> 00:24:11.920 align:middle line:90%
comments.

00:24:11.920 --> 00:24:14.650 align:middle line:84%
And it took me the longest time
to figure out what that was.

00:24:14.650 --> 00:24:18.180 align:middle line:84%
There's a cultural thing
that if you're the teacher,

00:24:18.180 --> 00:24:20.580 align:middle line:84%
and I ask you a
question, I'm telling you

00:24:20.580 --> 00:24:21.795 align:middle line:90%
you didn't teach me well.

00:24:21.795 --> 00:24:23.154 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Oh, I see, yes.

00:24:23.154 --> 00:24:25.570 align:middle line:84%
>>BOULTER: Well, that makes
sense if you look at it there.

00:24:25.570 --> 00:24:28.490 align:middle line:84%
But from our perspective, like,
I'd say, questions, comments?

00:24:28.490 --> 00:24:29.030 align:middle line:90%
Oh, right.

00:24:29.030 --> 00:24:29.639 align:middle line:90%
I'm in Taiwan.

00:24:29.639 --> 00:24:30.430 align:middle line:90%
There won't be any.

00:24:30.430 --> 00:24:33.170 align:middle line:84%
And the students are like, are
we allowed to ask questions?

00:24:33.170 --> 00:24:35.770 align:middle line:84%
And so I've dealt with
many Asian students

00:24:35.770 --> 00:24:37.200 align:middle line:84%
back at the
University of Calgary,

00:24:37.200 --> 00:24:40.469 align:middle line:84%
when I came back from Taiwan,
and they were all the same.

00:24:40.469 --> 00:24:42.010 align:middle line:84%
They were terrified
to ask questions.

00:24:42.010 --> 00:24:43.189 align:middle line:90%
And so I encouraged them.

00:24:43.189 --> 00:24:44.730 align:middle line:84%
And so at the
